<ul><li>The United States has always been a nation at odds with its professed aspirations of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_rights_in_the_United_States#Equality" class="extiw" title="w:Human rights in the United States">equality</a> and justice for all—from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genocide_of_indigenous_peoples#United_States_colonization_and_westward_expansion" class="extiw" title="w:Genocide of indigenous peoples">the genocide</a> of <a href="/wiki/Genocide_of_indigenous_peoples" title="Genocide of indigenous peoples">original inhabitants</a> to <a href="/wiki/Slavery_in_the_United_States" title="Slavery in the United States">slavery</a> to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreign_interventions_by_the_United_States" class="extiw" title="w:Foreign interventions by the United States">military aggression abroad</a>. But there have been periods in <a href="/wiki/History_of_the_United_States" title="History of the United States">our history</a> when courageous <a href="/wiki/Social_movements" class="mw-redirect" title="Social movements">social movements</a> have made significant advances. We must learn from those who’ve gone before us as we strive to build a movement that can tackle today’s injustices—and help all of us survive.
